description:
Driver MUST raise a client side error when attempting snapshot reads on <5.0. For example:
{code}
if session.option.snapshot and connection.maxWireVersion < 13:
    raise Exception('Snapshot reads require MongoDB 5.0 or later')
{code}
The unified session spec tests were updated to require this behavior. See https://github.com/mongodb/specifications/commit/d49fbe20f9b8e59a8705256f101e48a707faeb69

h3. Original description:
3.6 sharded cluster silently fail for readconcern "snapshot", in case collection does not exist. Consider adding client side validate for this case.

Thanks [~shane.harvey] for finding this.

{panel:title=Downstream Change Summary|titleBGColor=#239eb0|bgColor=#c2d2c2}
 * BSON corpus tests have been updated. Drivers should sync to [mongodb/specifications@b3b74c9|https://github.com/mongodb/specifications/commit/b3b74c97c3b4258a74c77f27a6bffb520918b42a].
 * Drivers should add a new constant corresponding to BSON binary subtype 0x07. "Column" should be included in its identifier (e.g. {{BinDataType::Column}} or {{BSON_SUBTYPE_COLUMN}}).
{panel}

h2. Description of Linked Ticket
Will be used for BSONColumn.

    {panel:title=Downstream Change Summary|titleBGColor=#239eb0|bgColor=#c2d2c2}
    For time-series collections, the `expireAfterSeconds` options is now specified as a part of the top-level collection options, rather than being nested inside the `timeseries` subobject. i.e.

{noformat}
{create: "coll", timeseries: {timeField: "time"}, expireAfterSeconds: 10}
{noformat}

When manually creating a time-series buckets collection, the `clusteredIndex` option now takes a boolean, rather than an object. i.e.

{noformat}
{create: "system.buckets.coll", clusteredIndex: true}
{noformat}

When using collMod to change the `expireAfterSeconds` of a time-series collection, `expireAfterSeconds` is now a top-level option and the previous `clusteredIndex` option has been removed. i.e.

{noformat}
{collMod: "coll", expireAfterSeconds: 20}
{noformat}
    {panel}

    h2. Description of Linked Ticket
    The API for specifying TTL on a time-series collection looks like this:
{noformat}
db.createCollection('ts', {timeseries: {timeField: 't', expireAfterSeconds: 3600}}); {noformat}
However, to change the "expireAfterSeconds" value, users have to specify a completely different "clusteredIndex" option:
{noformat}
db.runCommand({collMod: 'ts', clusteredIndex: {expireAfterSeconds: 10}}) {noformat}
This is confusing and we should make the API consistent between operations.

The driver CSFLE docs example code uses the admin database for the key vault. This is considered bad practice, particularly on Atlas (if even allowed). Correcting this is important, as we're preparing for the upcoming World announcements, which emphasize best practices for highly confidential customer workloads.

For example, the [PHPLIB CSFLE tutorial has|https://www.mongodb.com/docs/php-library/current/tutorial/client-side-encryption/#automatic-encryption-and-decryption]:

{code:php}
'keyVaultNamespace' => 'admin.datakeys'
{code}
 
cc [~behackett] [~rachelle.palmer] [~cynthia.braund] for awareness

